The paper discusses a method for building computers that can answer questions on any subject, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). The paper specifically focuses on learning to map questions to vectorial feature representations, which is a common technique in machine learning and artificial intelligence. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). Additionally, the paper discusses optimization procedures and weak supervision, which are common topics in the sub-categories of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses querying knowledge bases, which falls under the sub-category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper uses stochastic gradient descent and fine-tuning, which are common techniques in the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
